.Dd May 28, 2026
.Dt XTC_LOG 3
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm xtc_log_create ,
.Nm xtc_log_destroy ,
.Nm xtc_log_write ,
.Nm xtc_log_drain ,
.Nm XTC_LOG_DEBUG_F ,
.Nm XTC_LOG_INFO_F ,
.Nm XTC_LOG_WARN_F ,
.Nm XTC_LOG_ERROR_F
.Nd async ring-buffer logger
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.In xtc.h
.In xtc_log.h
.Ft int
.Fn xtc_log_create "const xtc_log_opts_t *opts" "xtc_log_t **out"
.Ft void
.Fn xtc_log_destroy "xtc_log_t *log"
.Ft int
.Fn xtc_log_write "xtc_log_t *log" "xtc_log_level_t level" "const char *fmt" "..."
.Ft int
.Fn xtc_log_drain "xtc_log_t *log"
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm xtc_log
is a predictable-latency logger: callers append records to an
in-memory ring buffer; a sink consumer drains the ring on a timer
or explicit flush.  Producers never block; if the ring is full,
the oldest record is dropped silently.
.Pp
Levels:
.Dv XTC_LOG_DEBUG ,
.Dv XTC_LOG_INFO ,
.Dv XTC_LOG_WARN ,
.Dv XTC_LOG_ERROR .
A configurable global level filter elides cheaper records before
formatting.
.Pp
.Sy Sinks
.Pq Va opts.sink_fd
or
.Va opts.sink_fn :
records are written to either a file descriptor (stdout, syslog
fd, etc.) or a user callback.
.Pp
The
.Fn XTC_LOG_*_F
macros are convenience wrappers that look up a process-default
.Vt xtc_log_t
and call
.Fn xtc_log_write
with the right level.
.Pp
.Fn xtc_log_drain
forces an immediate flush; called from the metrics proc on a
timer or at process exit.
.Sh EXAMPLES
.Bd -literal -offset indent
xtc_log_t *log;
xtc_log_opts_t opts = XTC_LOG_OPTS_DEFAULT;
opts.sink_fd = STDOUT_FILENO;
opts.min_level = XTC_LOG_INFO;

xtc_log_create(&opts, &log);
XTC_LOG_INFO_F("server started on port %d", port);
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr xtc_cfg 3 ,
.Xr xtc_stats 3 ,
.Xr xtc 7
.Sh HISTORY
Appeared in xtc 0.1.
